\begin_layout Subsubsection
Hello, World
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's create a new page for our wiki, under our application's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

/resources/
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 subdirectory.
 We'll call it 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

page.s.html
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 We'll start simple:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

<html>
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

<body>
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	<p>Hello, world.
 This page will become a wiki very soon!</p>
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

</body>
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

</html>
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Browse to 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "http://localhost:8080/wiki/page/"
target "http://localhost:8080/wiki/page/"

\end_inset

 to see it.
 Note that you do not need to restart Prudence if you're only adding or
 changing pages: Prudence will pick up these changes on-demand, on-the-fly,
 and make sure to compile and recompile as necessary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You'll notice that even though the file has a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

.s.html
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 extension, Prudence does not use the extension for the URL.
 This is because that extension is entirely an implementation concern on
 your end: there's no reason for the user to have to see it, nor to have
 it clutter the URL.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also notice the trailing slash: it's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

page/
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, not 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

page
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\emph on
Prudence enforces trailing slashes.
 
\emph default
This allows your relative URLs to be clear and unambiguous.
 For example, to insert an image in our page, we could do this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

<img src="../images/logo.png" />
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Without
\emph default
 a trailing slash, you would not need the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

../
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, but 
\emph on
with 
\emph default
the trailing slash, it's 
\emph on
necessary
\emph default
.
 If you don't pick one of the two options, handling relative URLs quickly
 becomes messy.
 So why have we decided to standardize on trailing slashes? Because it gives
 you more flexibility: for example, instead of saving our page 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

page.s.html
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, we could have saved it as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

page/index.s.html
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and the 
\emph on
URL would be identical
\emph default
.
 As you will see, the trailing slash principle is used throughout Prudence
 to allow many such conveniences, for both external URLs and for internal
 library URIs.
 You'll see us constantly ending our URIs in slashes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Multilingual
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The application skeleton uses JavaScript (
\emph on
server
\emph default
-side JavaScript; it has nothing to do with the code running inside web
 browsers), but Prudence also supports Python, Ruby, PHP, Lua, Groovy and
 Clojure.
 To use them, you would first need to 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "install them using Sincerity"
target "http://threecrickets.com/sincerity/ecosystem/language-plugins/"

\end_inset

.
 To try this out, let's install Python like so:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

sincerity add python : install
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We could then create a Python scriptlet:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

<%python
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

for x in range(0, 10):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	print x, '<br/>'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%>
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The low-level APIs are available for all supported languages.
