Note that, similarly to capturing, you can 
\bar under
interpolate conversation attributes (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "string-interpolation"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
 into the ID.
 For example, here we will automatically use a different dispatch ID according
 the protocol, either 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

session.HTTP
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

session.HTTPS
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

app.routes = {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	'/session/{sessionId}/': '@session.{p}'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
The Dispatch Map
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By default, to implement your dispatched resources, create a library named
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

/dispatched/
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, which is expected to change a global dict named 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

resources
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 That dict maps IDs to implementations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For our example, let's create a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

/libraries/dispatched.js
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 file:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

var UserResource = function() {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	this.handleInit = function(conversation) {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

		conversation.addMediaTypeByName('text/plain')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	this.handleGet = function(conversation) {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

		return 'This is user #' + conversation.locals.get('userId')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

resources = {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	session: {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

		handleInit: function(conversation) {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

			conversation.addMediaTypeByName('text/plain')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

		},
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

		handleGet: function(conversation) {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

			return 'This is session #' + conversation.locals.get('sessionId')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

		}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	},
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	user: new UserResource()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We've mapped the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

session
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 dispatch ID to a dict, and used simple JavaScript object-oriented programming
 for the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

user
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 dispatch ID.
 (Note that the Sincerity.Classes facility offers a comprehensive object-oriented
 system for JavaScript, but we preferred more straightforward code for this
 example.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As you can see, the resources.js file does not refer to URIs, but instead
 to dispatch IDs, which you can dispatch as you see fit.
 This is true URI/resource separation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These defaults are all configurable: see 
\bar under

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

app.dispatchers
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "app-dispatchers"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
 for more information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Other Programming Languages
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Resource dispatching is also supported for Python, Ruby, PHP, Lua, Groovy
 and Clojure, via alternate dispatchers.
 To use them, you must specify the dispatcher, which is simply the name
 of the language in lowercase, when you configure the dispatch.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

app.routes = {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	'/session/{sessionId}/': {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

		type: 'dispatch',
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

		id: 'session',
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

		dispatcher: 'python'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

You can also use the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

@
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 shortcut like so:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

app.routes = {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	'/session/{sessionId}/': '@python:session'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Inversion of Control (IoC)
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "resource-dispatching-ioc"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Object-oriented inheritance is one useful way to reuse code while allowing
 for special implementations.
 Additionally, Prudence allows for a straightforward 
\bar under
Inversion of Control mechanism (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "ioc"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For both capturing and dispatching, you can inject set values to 
\bar under
conversation.locals (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "conversation-locals"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
.
 You would need to use the long-form notation to do this.
 Here are examples for both a capture and a dispatch:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

app.routes = {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	'/user/{userId}/': {type: 'capture', uri: '/user/', locals: {style: 'simple'}},
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	'/user/{userId}/full/': {type: 'capture', uri: '/user/', locals: {style:
 'full'}},
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	'/user/{userId}/preferences/': {type: 'dispatch', id: 'user', locals: {section:
 'preferences'}},
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	'/user/{userId}/profile/: {type: 'dispatch', id: 'user', locals: {section:
 'profile'}}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that in each case two URI templates are captured/matched to the exact
 same resource, but the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

locals
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 dict used is different for each.
 In your resource implementations, you can then allow for different behavior
 according to the value of the set 
\bar under
conversation.local (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "conversation-locals"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

this.handleGet = function(conversation) {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	var section = conversation.locals.get('section')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	if (section == 'preferences') {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

		...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	else if (section == profile') {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

		...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This allows you to configure your resources in routing.js, rather than at
 their implementation code.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

control
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

inverted,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 via value injection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
app.errors
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app-errors"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By default, Prudence will display ready-made error pages if the response's
 HTTP status code is an error (>=400), but you can override these by settings
 your own custom pages:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

app.errors = {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	404: '/errors/not-found/',
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	500: '/errors/fail/'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The keys of the dict are status codes, while the values work like 
\bar under
captures (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "resource-capturing"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
.
 This means that you can implement your error pages using any kind of resource:
 manual, scriptlet or static.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If your error resource is mapped under 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

/resources/
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and you don't want it exposed, use the 
\bar under
capture-and-hide notation (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "capture-and-hide"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

app.errors = {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	404: '/errors/not-found/!'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is equivalent to explicitly hiding the URI in app.routes using the 
\bar under

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hidden
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 route type (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "hidden-route-type"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

app.routes = {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	'/errors/not-found/': '!'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 500 (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

internal server error
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) statuses caused by uncaught exceptions can be handled specially by 
\bar under
enabling debug mode (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "settings-errors"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\series bold
Warning:
\series default
 If you decide to implement your error pages using a 
\emph on
non
\emph default
-static resource, you run the risk of the resource code throwing an exception.
 If that happens, it would cause a 500 status code.
 If the original error was 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 500, then this would confuse the client and complicate debugging.
 However, if the original status code 
\emph on
was
\emph default
 500, then it could be much worse: the error would trigger your error page
 to be displayed again, which might throw the exception again\SpecialChar \ldots{}
 resulting
 in a stack overflow error.
 For these reasons, it's probably a good idea to implement your error pages
 as static resources, at least for production deployments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
app.hosts
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app-hosts"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Use app.hosts to assign the application to a base URI on one or more virtual
 hosts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The default configuration uses a single host, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

default
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 one, but you can add more, or even not have a single 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

default
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 host.
 Still, note that only a 
\emph on
single
\emph default
 application instance is used, even if attached to multiple hosts: for example,
 all 
\bar under
application.globals (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "application-globals"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
 are shared no matter which host a request is routed from.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To configure your hosts, and for a more complete discussion, see the 
\bar under
servers and hosts guide (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "hosts"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Bare Minimum
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You need to attach your application to at least one host to make it public.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

app.hosts = {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	'default': '/myapp/'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Note the required use of quotes around 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

default
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, due to it being a reserved keyword in JavaScript.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you don't have an app.hosts definition, or if it is empty, then your applicati
on 
\emph on
will not be publicly available over HTTP
\emph default
.
 However, it will still run, and be available as an internal API.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Internal Host
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "the-internal-host"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

internal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is a reserved host name, used to represent the 
\bar under
internal URI-space (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "internal-uri-space"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By default, applications are always attached to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

internal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 host, with the base URI being the application's subdirectory name.
 However, you can override this default should you require:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

app.hosts = {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	'default': '/myapp/',
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	internal: '/special/'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Multiple Hosts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here's an example of attaching the app to two different virtual hosts, with
 different base URIs under each:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

app.hosts = {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	'default': '/myapp/',
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	'privatehost': '/admin/'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you need your application to sometimes behave differently on each host,
 you 
\emph on
might
\emph default
 be able to 
\emph on
indirectly
\emph default
 discover the host that routed the request using the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "conversation.reference.baseRef API"
target "http://threecrickets.com/api/javascript/?namespace=conversation&item=conversation.reference"

\end_inset

.
 This will always be the application's root URI.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

if (conversation.reference.baseRef.path == '/myapp/') {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
app.dispatchers
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app-dispatchers"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section is optional, and is used to change the way your application's
 dispatching works.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Setting the Default Dispatcher
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As seen above in 
\bar under
resource dispatching (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "resource-dispatching"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
, if you you do not specify the dispatcher when configuring a 
\bar under

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dispatch
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 route type (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "dispatch-route-type"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
, it will default to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

javascript
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 dispatcher.
 You may change the default like so:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

app.routes = {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	'/session/{sessionId}/': '@session'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

app.dispatchers = {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	'default': 'python'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the above, our 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

@session
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 dispatch will be using the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

python
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 dispatcher.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Setting the Dispatch Map
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We've also seen that by default the dispatcher will attempt to execute your
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

/dispatched/
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 library in order to initialize the dispatch map.
 However, you may change this location per dispatcher like so:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

app.dispatchers = {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	javascript: '/mylib/mydispatchmap/'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is especially useful if you're using more than one dispatcher in your
 routing, because each dispatcher would need its own resource map.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

app.routes = {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	'/user/{userId}/': '@user',
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	'/session/{sessionId}/': '@python:session',
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	'/page/{pageId}/': '@groovy:page'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

app.dispatchers = {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	javascript: '/mylib/javascript-dispatchmap/',
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	python: '/mylib/python-dispatchmap/',
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	groovy: '/mylib/groovy-dispatchmap/'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Custom Dispatchers
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "custom-dispatchers"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Custom dispatchers are very useful for 
\bar under
integrating alternative templating engines (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "view-templates"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
 into Prudence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under the hood, resource dispatching is handled by the URI capturing mechanism:
 the URI is captured to a special manual resource---the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dispatcher
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

---with an 
\bar under
injected value (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "ioc"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
 specifying the ID of resource to which it should dispatch.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prudence's default dispatchers can be found in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

/libraries/scripturian/prudence/dispatchers/
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 directory of your container.
 For example, the JavaScript dispatcher is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

/libraries/scripturian/prudence/dispatchers/javascript.js
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 You are encouraged to look at the code there in order to understand how
 dispatching works: it's quite straightforward delegation of the 
\bar under
entry points of a manual resource (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "manual-resources"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, you can also write your own dispatchers to handle different dispatching
 paradigms.
 To configure them, you will need to use a long-form for app.dispatchers.
 For example, here we override the default 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

javascript
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 dispatcher:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

app.dispatchers = {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	special: {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

		dispatcher: '/dispatchers/special-dispatcher/',
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

		customValue1: 'hello',
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

		customValue2: 'world'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dispatcher code (a standard manual resource) would be in a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

/libraries/dispatchers/special-dispatcher.js
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 file under your application's subdirectory.
 You would be able to access the dispatch ID there as the injected 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

prudence.dispatcher.id
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\bar under
conversation.local (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "conversation-locals"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

customValue1
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

customValue2
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 would be 
\bar under
application.globals (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "application-globals"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

prudence.dispatcher.special.customValue1
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

prudence.dispatcher.special.customValue2
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You can also override the default dispatchers:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

app.dispatchers = {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	javascript: {
\end_layout

