When a resource gets hit by a request for the first time, there will likely
 be an initial delay.
 Your code may have to be compiled, or, if it has been cached, would at
 least have to be loaded and initialized.
 But all that should happen very fast: the more serious delay would be caused
 by initializing subsystems and libraries, such as connecting to databases,
 logging in to external services, etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another source for delay is that, if you are 
\bar under
caching pages (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "server-side-caching"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
