\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

if (null !== session) {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	session.value = 'newsession'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	session.save()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ask the client to create a new cookie using 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "conversation.createCookie"
target "http://threecrickets.com/api/javascript/?namespace=conversation&item=conversation.createCookie"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

var session = conversation.createCookie('session')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

session.value = 'newsession'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

session.save()
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that createCookie will retrieve the cookie if it already exists.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When sending cookies 
\emph on
to
\emph default
 the client, you can set the following attributes 
\emph on
in addition
\emph default
 to those mentioned above, but note that you 
\emph on
cannot
\emph default
 retrieve them later:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
maxAge: age in seconds, after which the client should delete the cookie;
 maxAge=0 deletes the cookie immediately, while maxAge=-1 (the default)
 asks the client to keep the cookie only for the duration of the “session”
 (this is defined by the client; for most web browsers this means that the
 cookie will be deleted when the browser is closed)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
secure: true if the cookie is meant to be used only in secure connections
 (defaults to false)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
accessRestricted: true if the cookie is meant to be used only in authenticated
 connections (defaults to false)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
comment: some clients store this, some discard it
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You can ask the client to delete a cookie by calling its 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

delete
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 method.
 Note that this is identical to setting maxAge=0 and calling 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

save
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Security Concerns
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You should never store any unencrypted secret data in cookies: though web
 browsers attempt to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sandbox
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 cookies, making sure that only the server (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

domain
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) that stored them can retrieve them, they can be hijacked by other means.
 Better yet, don't store 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 secrets in cookies, even if encrypted, because even encryptions can be
 hacked.
 A cautious exception can be made for 
\emph on
short-term
\emph default
 secrets: for example, if you store a session ID in a cookie, make sure
 to expire it on the server so that it cannot be used later by a hacker.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A separate security concern for users is that cookies can be used to surreptitio
usly track user activity.
 This works because any resource on a web page---even an image hosted by
 an advertising company---can use cookies, and can also track your client's
 IP address.
 Uses various heuristics it is possible to identify individual users and
 track parts of their browser history.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because of these security concerns, it is recommended that you devise a
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cookie policy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for users and make it public, assuming you require the use of cookies for
 your site.
 In particular, let users know which 3rd-party resources you are including
 in your web pages that may be storing cookies, and for what purpose.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cookies are a security concern for you, too: you cannot expect all your
 clients to be standard, friendly web browsers.
 Clients might not be honoring your requests for cookie modifications, and
 might be sending you cookies that you did not ask them to store.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Be careful with cookies! They are a hacker's playground.
\end_layout

