\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem is that you need an intermediary; and it could be a big problem.
 Consider that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

classic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 MVC, based around a thick controller layer, isn't as popular as it used
 to be.
 There, the controller does 
\emph on
as much as possible, 
\emph default
under the assumption of predictability, in order to automate the production
 of large, repetitive user interfaces.
 It thus handles form validation, binding of form fields to database columns,
 and even form flows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Forms, forms, as far as the eye can see.
 MVC was, and still is, the domain of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

enterprise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 user interfaces.
 It's telling that the manipulation of the data model is called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

business logic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: the use case for MVC really is big business for big businesses.
 At its best, MVC makes these repetitive stacks of forms easier to maintain
 in the long run.
 At its worst, programmers drown in an ocean of controller configuration
 files, fighting opaque layers of APIs that can only do what they were programme
d to do, but not what is needed for a sensible UI.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Outside of the big business world, where automation reigns supreme, UI implement
ations use more flexible derivatives of MVC, such as 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Model-View-Presenter (MVP)"
target "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Model%E2%80%93view%E2%80%93presenter"

\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

presenter,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 far from an opaque layer, is implemented directly by the programmer in
 code, often by inheriting classes that provide the basic predictable functional
ity.
 Depending on the variation you're using, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

business logic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 might even be in the presenter rather than the model.
 Still, MVP, like MVC, stems from the same anxiety about mixing model and
 view.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
MVC and the Web
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These two do not seem an obvious match.
 The web is RESTful, such that the user interface (the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

view
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) is no different from data (the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

model
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

): both are RESTful resources, implemented similarly.
 In other words, in REST 
\emph on
the model is the view
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Well, that's only really and entirely true for the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

classic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 web.
 Using JavaScript and other in-browser plugins, we get a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rich
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 web that acts no differently from desktop applications.
 The backend remains RESTful, essentially the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

model,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 with controllers/presenters as well as views implemented entirely client-side.
 You can do full-blown, conventional MVC with the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rich
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 web.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MVC, however, has found inroads into the 
\emph on
classic
\emph default
 web: there exist many frameworks that treat web pages as a pure 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

view,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 an approach they go so far as to enforce by allowing you to embed only
 limited templating code into your HTML.
 Some of these frameworks even allow you to configure the form flow, which
 they then use to generate an opaque URI-space for you, and can even sabotage
 the browser 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

back
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 button to enforce that flow.
 (MVC automation at its finest! Or worst\SpecialChar \ldots{}
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The impetus for these brutally extreme measures is similar to the one with
 which we started: a desire to decouple the user interface from everything
 else.
 HTML is the realm of web designers, not programmers, and mixing the work
 of both professions into a single file presents project management challenges.
 However, there's a productive distance between cleaning up HTML pages and
 full-blown MVC, which unfortunately not enough frameworks explore.
 And actually, not everything called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

MVC
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 really is MVC.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So what are we left with in Prudence? As you'll see, Prudence supports a
 straightforward MVP architecture while still adhering to RESTful principles.
 Read on, and consider if it would benefit your project to use it.
 Our recommendation is to use what works best for you and your development
 team.
\end_layout

