\begin_layout Subsection
View Templates
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "view-templates"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One size does not fit all.
 Almost every web framework comes with its own solution to templating, with
 its own idiosyncratic syntax and set of features, manifesting its own templatin
g philosophy.
 As you've probably picked up, Prudence's philosophy is that the programmer
 knows best: scriptlets should be able do 
\emph on
anything
\emph default
, and the programmer doesn't need to be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

protected
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from bad decisions via a dumbed-down, sandboxed templating domain language.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two common counter-arguments, which we don't think are very convincing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first is that the people designing the templates might not, in fact,
 know best: they might not be proficient programmers, but instead web designers
 who specialize in HTML/CSS coding and testing.
 They would be able to deal with a few inserted template codes, but not
 a full-blown programming language.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 programmers would be writing the controllers/presenters, and injecting
 values into the templates according to the web designers' needs.
 This argument carries less validity than it used to: proficient web designers
 these days need to know JavaScript, and if they can handle client-side
 JavaScript, they should be able to handle server-side JavaScript, too.
 Will they need to learn some new things? Yes, but learning a new templating
 language is no trivial task, either.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second counter-argument is about discipline: even competent programmers
 might be tempted to make 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shortcuts,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and insert 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

business logic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 into what should be purely a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

view.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 This would short-circuit the MVC separation and create hard-to-manage 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spaghetti
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 code.
 A restricted templating language could, then, enforce this discipline.
 This seems like a brutal solution: programmers get annoyed if their own
 platforms don't trust them, and in any case can circumvent these restrictions
 by writing plugins that would then do what they need.
 But the real issue is that discipline should be handled as a social issue
 of project management, not by tools.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In any case, we won't force our philosophy on you: Prudence has built in
 support for 
\bar under
two templating engines (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "templating-languages"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
, and it's easy to plug in a wide range of alternative templating engines
 into Prudence.
 If you're familiar and comfortable with a particular one, use it.
 We'll guide you in this section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are many templating engines you can use.
 The best performing and most minimal solutions are pure JVM libraries:
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "StringTemplate"
target "http://www.stringtemplate.org/"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Thymeleaf"
target "http://www.thymeleaf.org/"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Snippetory"
target "http://www.jproggy.org/snippetory/"

\end_inset

.
 However, the most popular ones use other languages, for example 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Jinja2"
target "http://jinja.pocoo.org/docs/"

\end_inset

 for Python.
 Below are examples per each type.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The technique we'll show for using both types is the same: writing a 
\bar under
custom dispatcher (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "custom-dispatchers"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
, so make sure you understand dispatching before you continue to read.
\end_layout

