\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are 
\bar under
route types (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "filtering-route-types"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
 used to add effects to resources.
 Though you can often code the same effect directly into a resource, filters
 are decoupled from resources, allowing you to reuse an effect on many resources
, which is especially useful with 
\bar under
mapping route types (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "mapping-route-types"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, filters are the 
\emph on
only 
\emph default
way to add effects to 
\bar under
static resources (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "static-resources"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
, which cannot themselves be programmed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because it's easy to enable and disable filters just by editing routing.js,
 filters are often used to add debugging and testing effects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Tutorial
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Filters are implemented similarly to 
\bar under
manual resources (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "manual-resources"

\end_inset

)
\bar default
: as source code files (in any supported language) with either or both filter
 entry points: handleBefore and handleAfter.
 The former is called before all requests reach the next (downstream) route
 type, and the latter is called on the way back, after the downstream finishes
 its work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's start with configuring our filter, using the 
\bar under

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

